    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27a.20"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">105 Neihardt Collection</note>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    Miss Christy Jo Froschheuser
                    517 <hi rend="caps">S.</hi> Lexington Ave.
                    Hastings, Nebraska
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>May 11, 1959</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Our eleventh-grade English class has just concluded the reading of your narrative, <hi rend="underline">The Song of Hugh Glass</hi>. Never before has anything I have read or seen impressed me so much that I felt an urge to write a letter of admiration. However, as the old saying goes, "There is a first time for everything."</p>
                
                <p>Our teacher's announcement that we would begin a study of your Hugh Glass episode was initially met with groans from part of the class. In the future we could visualize long assignments of boring poetry which we could hardly tolerate. After we began reading it, though, many of the students could not lay the book down. They had to find out what happened. Much to our surprise, it was very exciting--and what teenager doesn't crave excitement?</p>
                
                <p>Speaking for all of the students, I must tell you that <hi rend="underline">The Song of Hugh Glass</hi> was very well liked. However, I believe that the other students' likings for it were to a lesser--and different--degree than mine. I have always been sensitive to the beautiful things in life and to an artistic use of the words of our language. I received a thrill from your vivid descriptions, many of which I myself have sensed but never was able to express. Also, I have a much better idea of my heritage.</p>
                
                <p>Reading <hi rend="underline">The Song of Hugh Glass</hi> has given me a desire to read your other works. Thank you so much for making this enjoyment possible for me.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours truly,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Christy Jo Froschheuser</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
